sql:
SELECT customer_id, credit_score
FROM credit_scores
WHERE credit_score > 700;

SELECT COUNT(customer_id) AS total_customers
FROM customer_financials
WHERE credit_card_debt > annual_salary;

SELECT customer_id, SUM(investment_value) AS total_investment_value
FROM customer_financials
GROUP BY customer_id;

SELECT c.first_name, c.last_name
FROM customers c
INNER JOIN customer_financials cf ON c.customer_id = cf.customer_id;

SELECT AVG(annual_salary) AS average_annual_salary
FROM customers
WHERE car_purchase_amount > (SELECT AVG(car_purchase_amount) FROM customers);

external_knowledge:
- A credit score above 700 is generally considered to have 'gold standard' in financial trustworthiness;
- 'Financial anchor' refers to significant transactions, indicating the depth and scale of financial activity;
- 'Navigational beacon' and 'chart' are metaphors for the credit agency and the reason for the credit score, respectively, guiding the financial status of an individual.

- Credit score less than 700 is generally considered lower; 
- 'loan' transaction type refers to any form of borrowing;
- "recent" in this context means transactions that occurred in the current month.
